Now I understand all the types:

- `User` extends `DefaultUser` which has `{ id?, name?, email?, image? }`
- `Session` extends `DefaultSession` which has `{ user?: User, expires: ISODateString }`
- `JWT` extends `DefaultJWT` which has `{ name?, email?, picture?, sub?, iat?, exp?, jti? }` plus `Record<string, unknown>`

Since `JWT extends Record<string, unknown>`, it already allows arbitrary properties! So I can set `token.userId`, `token.role`, `token.deptId` without any type augmentation. They'll be typed as `unknown`, but that's fine.

For `Session.user`, I need to add `userId`, `role`, `deptId` properties. The `User` type has `{ id?, name?, email?, image? }`. I need to augment it to also have `role` and `deptId`.

The simplest approach is to use declaration merging:

```typescript
declare module "@auth/core/types" {
  interface User {
    role: string
    deptId: string
  }
}
```

This adds `role` and `deptId` to the `User` interface.

But wait, `role` is actually `UserRole` (an enum from Prisma). I should use the string type or the Prisma enum. Since we're not importing Prisma types in the auth config (to avoid circular deps), I'll just use `string` or a literal union type.

Actually, the values from Prisma's enum will be strings at runtime (PostgreSQL stores enums as strings). So `string` is fine.

